petent people doing important work, period. As for how to address it, I'm not one for complicated theories or drawn-out sensitivity sessions. What works is straightforward action. Make sure young people see examples that break the stereotypes. When my kids were growing up, I made certain they understood that competence matters more than categories. Evaluate people on their actual work, not on assumptions. Keep standards high but apply them fairly across the board. In my Buddhist practice, I've learned that attachment to fixed views causes suffering. These stereotypes are fixed views that harm both individuals and society. The solution isn't to lower standards or make excuses, it's to remove the artificial barriers and let people prove themselves through their efforts. Judge the delivery, not the driver, if you will. That's been my approach to life and work, and it seems to me that's what would help in STEM fields too.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is a 77-year-old woman with vocational education, self-employed as a delivery driver in LA. Key traits: very high conscientiousness (95), low openness (21), low agreeableness (26). This suggests someone practical, disciplined, direct, and not particularly warm or theoretical. She has Buddhist beliefs which may inform her perspective on attachment to fixed views. Her parents had vastly different education levels, giving her insight into how education and opportunity differ. Her age means she experienced more overt sexism historically. Her low openness suggests she'll be skeptical of abstract theories and prefer concrete, traditional solutions. Low agreeableness means she'll be blunt and unsentimental. High conscientiousness means she values competence and standards. The tone should be direct, no-nonsense, practical, with some personal experience woven in but not overly emotional or theoretical.","tone":"direct, practical, no-nonsense, somewhat blunt, drawing on personal experience, skeptical of abstract theories, focuse